00:49:09.377 --> 00:49:11.619
how dense the Universe has to
be to stop it.

00:49:11.619 --> 00:49:15.690
And so, what you expect is the
Universe is slowing down.

00:49:15.690 --> 00:49:18.126
Because you know you don't know
how much it's slowing down,

00:49:18.126 --> 00:49:19.847
whether it will stop the
expansion or not,

00:49:19.847 --> 00:49:21.570
but you expect it to be slowing
down.

00:49:21.570 --> 00:49:24.019
The punch line of this whole
part of the course,

00:49:24.019 --> 00:49:26.260
in order to anticipate where
we're going,

00:49:26.260 --> 00:49:29.011
is that, in fact,
we can measure the change in

00:49:29.011 --> 00:49:31.640
the expansion rate,
and it's speeding up,

00:49:31.640 --> 00:49:35.225
not slowing down.
This is very disturbing,

00:49:35.225 --> 00:49:38.109
because it means there's some
kind of pervasive cosmic

00:49:38.109 --> 00:49:40.548
anti-gravity,
which we call dark energy,

00:49:40.548 --> 00:49:42.599
because we don't know what it
is.

00:49:42.599 --> 00:49:45.648
And that's basically the punch
line of this whole section of

00:49:45.648 --> 00:49:48.486
the course.
But you could imagine that

00:49:48.486 --> 00:49:51.736
there is a change in the
expansion rate,

00:49:51.736 --> 00:49:55.654
either positive or negative,
and that, therefore,

00:49:55.654 --> 00:49:58.390
various different outcomes are
possible.

